;In DOCS:

;No way to "Disable" entire program, only individual devices.
;  Must Uninstall and then Reinstall/Reinitialize.
;Digital joystick BIOS recognition call only works if a Joystick is installed
;  and Enabled
;Can't use "-" for Switches, since use it for Ranges in Ignore Switch.
;Can't find good Multi-Joystick Interface.  May need to create one in final
;    release of program, but won't do it unless there is a possiblity of
;    some program (besides JOYKEYS) actually using it.  A "good" API
;    would include multiple joysticks, multiple interface types (standard
;    Game Ports, Parallel Ports, Serial ports, USB, remote/internet control,
;    Keyboard, etc.), multiple input control types (control "groups",
;    self-centering axes, self-closing axes/Throttles, non-return Axes/Sliders,
;    polar/rotating axes, 4-way/8-Way D-Pads/hat switches,
;    buttons/button groups, toggle/selection switches, and anything else that
;    might be used as an put, including things like body gloves, flight
;    helmets, etc.).  The API would also need include Force Feedback (a
;    standard way to send data to the Joystick).  MUCH complication involved
;    here -- to much to handle right now.
;  MULTIJOY handles up to 6 simple joysticks (two axes and two buttons each).
;    Not enough joysticks, buttons, or axes to be really useful.  Doesn't
;    define how to have multiple drivers in memory at same time (e.g., keyboard,
;    prallel, standard, USB).
;  SGDI (from Art of Assembly Language) doesn't handle multiple joysticks.
;    Does allow several Buttons and Axes (Pots), but doesn't have a way
;    to logically "combine" buttons or axes (such as 15-button protocol or
;    4-way/8-way hat switch).  Requires Axes return values to be "normalized",
;    which is a problem on real joysticks without requiring the user to pan
;    the axes.  Doesn't define how to have multiple drivers in memory at
;    same time.  In spite of severe shortcomings, maybe the best choice
;    to start with to extend into an appopriate API.  Don't know of any
;    programs that actually use it, though there might be some.
;  GrIP is proprietary, not clearly defined.  Really designed as an SDK,
;    not an API.  "Natively" allows Protected Mode and Real Mode Interfaces.
;    Does allow multiple joysticks, Defines Axes, Buttons, POV Hats,
;    & "Velocity-sensitive Buttons" (whatever those are).  POV Hats are always
;    4-way???)
;Gas Pedal is 5th Axis, not third, even though it appears third in the
;  coordinate list (BX).
;We tried to "automate" provisioning, but turned out to be harder to
;  understand than just straight mappings.  Some sort of GUI could make
;  this easier, but even that won't make it "easy" to understand with
;  multiple control types and multiple joysticks.  No true standards, too
;  many different kinds of joysticks (even in Windows, requires a custom
;  driver for each joystick with graphics, no such things as a "universal"
;  joystick driver in Windows, except for simple 2-axis, 2-button
;  analog joysticks.  Definitely need to make youself some batch files/
;  environment variables, since defauls will most likely not be what you want!
;Mention Re-Enable somehow


